WEBVTT

00:00:00.010 --> 00:00:07.480
Yeah, so the title's actually kind of a pun or

00:00:07.480 --> 00:00:08.000
something.

00:00:08.010 --> 00:00:10.460
So, yeah, so hi, I'm Paul Syvers

00:00:10.460 --> 00:00:12.860
on from the Naval Research Lab.

00:00:12.870 --> 00:00:16.200
If you don't know me, the thing I'm probably

00:00:16.210 --> 00:00:20.190
most known for is I invented onion routing with a couple of

00:00:20.190 --> 00:00:23.200
my NRL colleagues forever ago, back in the 90s

00:00:23.200 --> 00:00:25.960
, and then a few years later with a couple of non

00:00:25.960 --> 00:00:29.900
-NRL colleagues created a version of that we called Tor

00:00:29.900 --> 00:00:30.240
.

00:00:30.260 --> 00:00:33.520
And this is the main thing I've been working on pretty

00:00:33.520 --> 00:00:34.740
much ever since.

00:00:34.770 --> 00:00:43.330
What I've been working on mostly for the last several

00:00:43.330 --> 00:00:51.170
years is the question of there's a lot of domain names

00:00:51.170 --> 00:00:53.800
that have associated onion addresses.

00:00:53.800 --> 00:00:56.100
If you don't know what an onion address is, I

00:00:56.130 --> 00:00:58.060
don't have enough time to explain it.

00:00:58.070 --> 00:01:01.280
So, for our purposes, you can just think of it

00:01:01.280 --> 00:01:04.260
as pretty much like a PLC did because it's a

00:01:04.260 --> 00:01:07.840
cryptographically self-certifying address.

00:01:07.840 --> 00:01:14.940
And domain names are generally human meaningful, and onion addresses are

00:01:14.940 --> 00:01:18.480
these cryptographically things that are not, and turns out

00:01:18.480 --> 00:01:26.610
how to discover when things are associated and how to be sure

00:01:26.620 --> 00:01:31.070
they're bound together has all kinds of problems that, has

00:01:31.070 --> 00:01:37.750
all kinds of problems, and which I have spelled out in

00:01:37.750 --> 00:01:40.040
all of these papers that I'm not going to actually talk

00:01:40.040 --> 00:01:43.120
about, but that's there if you want to go look

00:01:43.120 --> 00:01:46.560
for them, and then also, fortunately, solutions to these

00:01:46.560 --> 00:01:46.660
.

00:01:46.660 --> 00:01:52.940
What are the goals of the work here is to sort of

00:01:52.940 --> 00:01:58.710
synthesize those things with, at proto-identities,

00:01:58.710 --> 00:02:02.900
so handles and dids, with a couple of goals.

00:02:02.900 --> 00:02:08.570
One is to improve and generalize blue sky verified accounts,

00:02:08.620 --> 00:02:13.250
to be more than they are now, explicit about who the

00:02:13.250 --> 00:02:16.410
verifier is, and also to provide some context, to

00:02:16.410 --> 00:02:21.470
be decentralized, so it's not limited just to the blue

00:02:21.470 --> 00:02:26.480
sky trusted verifiers, and also open, so that anybody

00:02:26.480 --> 00:02:33.600
can have a verified identity, and in addition, we want

00:02:33.600 --> 00:02:37.330
to synthesize these together in a way that allows us to

00:02:37.330 --> 00:02:43.580
have self-certifying meaningful identities that are consistently transparent,

00:02:43.580 --> 00:02:46.930
that are blocking resistant, this is one of the things onion

00:02:46.930 --> 00:02:51.530
services provide in a way I won't explain, and robust

00:02:51.530 --> 00:02:56.080
to TLS certificate hijack, and also, everything we

00:02:56.080 --> 00:03:00.220
've done is sort of fully backwards compatible, so that if

00:03:00.220 --> 00:03:05.000
you are running something that doesn't know anything about our stuff

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:07.640
, as long as it uses the standard protocols, nothing's

00:03:07.640 --> 00:03:08.580
going to break.

00:03:08.580 --> 00:03:11.610
You won't get the advantages, but nothing's going to

00:03:11.610 --> 00:03:12.250
break.

00:03:12.270 --> 00:03:15.830
So this is joint work with the force of nature, who

00:03:15.830 --> 00:03:20.780
is Nick Jarakinas, who's right there.

00:03:20.790 --> 00:03:23.440
And yes.

00:03:23.440 --> 00:03:26.050
So suppose, as an example, I didn't know about

00:03:26.050 --> 00:03:28.340
smoke signal, and Nick says, oh, here's this

00:03:28.350 --> 00:03:30.750
cool thing, smoke signal, you should check it out.

00:03:30.760 --> 00:03:34.200
And let's assume that he and I have a trusted channel

00:03:34.200 --> 00:03:38.080
over signal, and we've validated that, that I trust

00:03:38.080 --> 00:03:42.670
Nick about identifiers for domains, or maybe just for particular

00:03:42.700 --> 00:03:46.320
domains, we can come back to that.

00:03:46.320 --> 00:03:49.030
But what if smoke signal.

00:03:49.240 --> 00:03:51.990
events has a TLS hijack?

00:03:52.020 --> 00:03:54.430
So just what I mean by that, well, if you

00:03:54.440 --> 00:03:55.720
go to smoke signal.

00:03:55.780 --> 00:03:58.580
events, you get the little, the usual lock icon

00:03:58.580 --> 00:03:58.810
.

00:03:58.820 --> 00:04:02.070
And if you click on that, you can see a certificate

00:04:02.070 --> 00:04:05.360
that says that an authority, in this case, let's

00:04:05.360 --> 00:04:09.010
encrypt, says, oh, the key that's authentic

00:04:09.010 --> 00:04:13.870
ating this connection is, in fact, associated with the name

00:04:13.870 --> 00:04:15.100
smoke signal.

00:04:15.100 --> 00:04:17.770
So that's great.

00:04:17.800 --> 00:04:22.150
Only problem is, it's way too easy to obtain bog

00:04:22.150 --> 00:04:24.460
us TLS certificates.

00:04:24.460 --> 00:04:27.180
It's not completely trivial, and a lot of people have

00:04:27.380 --> 00:04:29.340
done a lot of work to make it harder, but I

00:04:29.340 --> 00:04:31.840
don't think there's a problem that's going away anytime

00:04:32.040 --> 00:04:32.420
soon.

00:04:32.420 --> 00:04:35.620
It's just a big, bad problem.

00:04:35.630 --> 00:04:39.570
So the answer, what if it gets hijacked, is

00:04:39.570 --> 00:04:44.780
somebody can basically set up their own version of smoke signal,

00:04:44.780 --> 00:04:48.540
and get me to think whatever about upcoming events, or maybe

00:04:48.540 --> 00:04:53.900
reveal some kind of sensitive information in the course of RSV

00:04:53.900 --> 00:04:57.690
Ping, so in general, bad situation.

00:04:57.700 --> 00:05:02.150
But what if instead of giving me just the link to smoke

00:05:02.150 --> 00:05:03.070
signal.

00:05:03.070 --> 00:05:08.600
events, the URL includes the PLC did for smoke

00:05:08.600 --> 00:05:10.580
signal.

00:05:10.590 --> 00:05:12.600
events.

00:05:12.600 --> 00:05:16.500
And again, we have the trusted channel that I'm getting

00:05:16.500 --> 00:05:18.520
things from, Nick from.

00:05:18.520 --> 00:05:23.140
Now if I go and follow that URL, we have a

00:05:23.160 --> 00:05:30.540
Firefox extension that Nick created, that ultimately I would like this

00:05:30.540 --> 00:05:33.560
to just be built into Firefox, but you need to crawl

00:05:33.590 --> 00:05:34.840
before you walk.

00:05:34.840 --> 00:05:43.010
So this extension checks that there's a header that

00:05:43.010 --> 00:05:45.140
gets sent.

00:05:45.140 --> 00:05:48.120
And it makes sure that the key that's on the header

00:05:48.120 --> 00:05:53.280
is in fact associated with this did, and further that the

00:05:53.480 --> 00:06:00.850
did that's in the did document matches the did that was

00:06:00.850 --> 00:06:02.720
in the URL.

00:06:02.730 --> 00:06:06.230
As opposed to if, for example, the did was not

00:06:06.230 --> 00:06:09.680
a good did, then you would fail the checks.

00:06:09.690 --> 00:06:12.260
So great.

00:06:12.260 --> 00:06:16.710
So this provides what I like to call dirt simple trust.

00:06:16.740 --> 00:06:19.410
The idea is I need, all I need is the address

00:06:19.660 --> 00:06:20.980
and I'm kind of done.

00:06:20.980 --> 00:06:21.980
That's enough.

00:06:21.980 --> 00:06:24.650
I can't, I can't be hijacked or anything

00:06:24.900 --> 00:06:29.070
as long as we have this I discovered it in this way

00:06:29.070 --> 00:06:30.080
.

00:06:30.090 --> 00:06:32.720
Relatedly, it also offers what I would call authority

00:06:32.720 --> 00:06:33.700
independence.

00:06:33.700 --> 00:06:37.690
So the idea is no authority, no CA can say,

00:06:37.760 --> 00:06:41.360
oh, no, here's the new key for, for

00:06:41.360 --> 00:06:47.060
smoke signal, because they don't control the key that is

00:06:47.060 --> 00:06:50.920
associated with the did, I can't be tricked about that

00:06:51.090 --> 00:06:51.620
.

00:06:51.620 --> 00:06:57.450
So because I learned of this URL from Nick, and because

00:06:57.450 --> 00:07:02.520
it passed the checks when I tried to connect to it,

00:07:02.560 --> 00:07:06.960
I can trust that Nick told me that the handle and did

00:07:06.960 --> 00:07:10.950
are in fact bound together, and further that, because I

00:07:10.950 --> 00:07:14.360
trust Nick, I can trust that they are bound together.

00:07:14.360 --> 00:07:18.140
But we're not quite done, because in order to do

00:07:18.140 --> 00:07:21.640
this, we had to have this, you know, signal

00:07:21.650 --> 00:07:22.630
exchange.

00:07:22.640 --> 00:07:25.210
And Nick has been very tolerant of me, but I think

00:07:25.210 --> 00:07:28.520
if every time I wanted to have a secure connection with anything

00:07:28.520 --> 00:07:31.110
, I had to have a signal communication with him, maybe

00:07:31.110 --> 00:07:33.290
that would try even Nick's patients.

00:07:33.300 --> 00:07:39.370
So we, therefore, have it automated so that we have

00:07:39.450 --> 00:07:45.050
a record that you get a signed header that's signed by

00:07:45.050 --> 00:07:46.830
, say, njrakinis.

00:07:46.830 --> 00:07:50.530
me, as well as by smoke signal, that says that

00:07:50.790 --> 00:07:52.280
these are bound together.

00:07:52.300 --> 00:07:56.860
And further, and this is where I'm introducing contextual labels

00:07:56.860 --> 00:08:00.000
, it could have a label like, for example, this

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:02.460
is a Nick project, this is a project that Nick did

00:08:02.460 --> 00:08:02.710
.

00:08:02.730 --> 00:08:07.170
So let's contrast this with the way Blue Sky currently handles

00:08:07.260 --> 00:08:09.000
verified accounts.

00:08:09.040 --> 00:08:14.120
So you can, Blue Sky will directly verify somebody's account

00:08:14.120 --> 00:08:18.550
as belonging to someone, but they also have a handful of

00:08:18.550 --> 00:08:21.020
trusted verifiers.

00:08:21.030 --> 00:08:23.520
And that's fine, but it has some limitations.

00:08:23.520 --> 00:08:28.390
For one thing, you have to be important in order to

00:08:28.390 --> 00:08:31.020
get a verified account.

00:08:31.020 --> 00:08:33.980
Or you have to be affiliated with one of these, there

00:08:33.980 --> 00:08:36.900
's about 20 currently trusted verifiers.

00:08:36.900 --> 00:08:39.620
Most of them are journalism organizations, and I mean, I

00:08:39.820 --> 00:08:42.080
think that's great, but the rest of us are just

00:08:42.080 --> 00:08:44.340
SOL if we don't have, you know, one of

00:08:44.340 --> 00:08:45.890
these affiliations.

00:08:45.900 --> 00:08:52.360
So what we have is it supports that kind of functionality,

00:08:52.360 --> 00:08:57.390
and I think should replace it.

00:08:57.400 --> 00:08:59.920
So you can just do the same thing, that's what

00:08:59.930 --> 00:09:02.820
I've got here on the left, your left, whatever

00:09:02.830 --> 00:09:03.070
.

00:09:03.080 --> 00:09:05.800
But it doesn't have to be centralized like that.

00:09:05.880 --> 00:09:09.060
You could also have, say, like the town of Spring

00:09:09.060 --> 00:09:14.140
field is going to tell you what the local cities are in

00:09:14.140 --> 00:09:14.690
Springfield.

00:09:14.700 --> 00:09:17.900
So you might have a local news source in Springfield,

00:09:17.900 --> 00:09:21.830
and this is a good way you can resist pink slime journalism

00:09:21.830 --> 00:09:25.980
because you won't have some, you know, somebody from

00:09:25.980 --> 00:09:29.140
far away masquerading as being from Springfield.

00:09:29.210 --> 00:09:32.400
Or it can also be even at the individual level.

00:09:32.400 --> 00:09:33.940
So this scales both up and down.

00:09:33.950 --> 00:09:37.370
So like if you're somebody, I just made this entity

00:09:37.370 --> 00:09:39.860
up, as far as I know, but you know,

00:09:39.870 --> 00:09:42.790
you have somebody named Vegan Piper, maybe you trust them

00:09:42.820 --> 00:09:46.540
about where there are vegan restaurants around.

00:09:46.550 --> 00:09:48.780
But maybe you don't trust them about that.

00:09:48.780 --> 00:09:51.950
But you do trust them about, you know, bagpipe

00:09:51.950 --> 00:09:52.860
supplies.

00:09:52.860 --> 00:09:57.050
So you can choose which you want to trust them on.

00:09:57.070 --> 00:09:59.580
So I don't have a lot of time here.

00:09:59.590 --> 00:10:00.780
So that's it.

00:10:00.780 --> 00:10:03.860
And I'll be happy to take any questions.

00:10:03.870 --> 00:10:12.270
Do we have any questions for

00:10:12.270 --> 00:10:14.820
Paul?

00:10:14.860 --> 00:10:16.850
We've got a couple of minutes.

00:10:16.860 --> 00:10:17.850
Hooray.

00:10:17.870 --> 00:10:18.850
Yes.

00:10:18.860 --> 00:10:19.850
All right.

00:10:19.860 --> 00:10:22.460
For the record, those of us at Blue Sky also think

